WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:23.070 --> 00:00:25.500
&gt;&gt; Georgette Dorn: Good
afternoon, I'm Georgette Dorn

00:00:25.500 --> 00:00:27.850
and I'm the Chief of
the Hispanic Division.

00:00:27.850 --> 00:00:29.670
It's a great pleasure
to welcome all of you

00:00:29.670 --> 00:00:32.730
to this wonderful library and
this wonderful collection.

00:00:32.730 --> 00:00:35.330
We have the most extensive
Latin American, Spanish

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:37.650
and Portuguese collection in
the world, and not just books

00:00:37.650 --> 00:00:40.700
and periodicals, but
also manuscripts, maps,

00:00:40.700 --> 00:00:44.900
voice recordings, music,
films and even artefacts

00:00:44.900 --> 00:00:46.900
in the [inaudible]
collection and more

00:00:46.900 --> 00:00:48.860
than 7 million maps and atlases.

00:00:48.860 --> 00:00:51.880
So, it really is worth
being in and beginning

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:53.180
with the Hispanic reading room

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:54.480
because it's a beautiful
reading room

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:56.390
in the Jefferson Building
on the second floor.

00:00:56.390 --> 00:00:59.230
It is the oldest foreign area
reading room in the library.

00:00:59.230 --> 00:01:02.760
It began in 1939, so it
is now a great pleasure

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:08.730
to welcome here David Castillo
and Dr. William Eggington,

00:01:08.730 --> 00:01:10.610
and Patricia, and I'm not
sure what your last name,

00:01:10.610 --> 00:01:12.850
but Talia will introduce you.

00:01:12.850 --> 00:01:15.210
And it's a pleasure to
introduce Talia Guzman-Gonzalez

00:01:15.210 --> 00:01:20.940
who is the, la madre de
este evento tan importante,

00:01:20.940 --> 00:01:23.510
Talia Guzman-Gonzalez

00:01:23.510 --> 00:01:35.650
[ Applause ]

00:01:35.650 --> 00:01:37.060
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez:
Thank you, everyone

00:01:37.060 --> 00:01:39.590
and good afternoon
for, you know,

00:01:39.590 --> 00:01:41.950
welcome to the Library
of Congress.

00:01:41.950 --> 00:01:44.880
My name is Talia Guzman-Gonzalez
and I am a reference librarian

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:48.080
and Lusen Brazilian specialist
in the Hispanic Division.

00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:51.740
It is my great pleasure to
welcome you to this presentation

00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:54.620
of medialities, reading
reality in the age

00:01:54.620 --> 00:01:58.600
of inflationary media
composed a cuatro manos

00:01:58.600 --> 00:02:03.630
by two great scholars David
Castillo and William Eggington.

00:02:03.630 --> 00:02:08.180
I am very thankful to Patricia
for agreeing to being here

00:02:08.180 --> 00:02:11.460
and moderating the conversation
that I'm sure is going

00:02:11.460 --> 00:02:15.770
to be really provocative
and exciting.

00:02:15.770 --> 00:02:18.150
I will keep my introduction
short so we can move

00:02:18.150 --> 00:02:22.820
on to the event, but I would
also like to invite everyone

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:27.960
to stop by the lobby and see
the exhibit that the people

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:31.970
from Rare Books and Special
Collections put together

00:02:31.970 --> 00:02:35.450
for us today with
some wonderful items,

00:02:35.450 --> 00:02:37.940
including the first
edition of Don Quixote,

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:41.920
so please stop by
and take a peek.

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:45.900
So, our speakers today
are David Castillo,

00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:49.390
David Castillo is the Director
or the Humanities Institute

00:02:49.390 --> 00:02:52.800
at SUNY Buffalo and Professor
of Spanish in the Department

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:55.800
of Romance Languages and
Literature where he served

00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:59.290
as Chair between 2009 and 2015.

00:02:59.290 --> 00:03:03.670
He's the author of "Baroque
Horrors, Roots of the Fantastic

00:03:03.670 --> 00:03:07.630
in the Age of Curiosities",
published in 2012

00:03:07.630 --> 00:03:12.910
and he is also the co-author of
"Zombie Talk, Culture, History

00:03:12.910 --> 00:03:18.680
and Politics", published
in 2016 among other books.

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:21.020
His fields of research
includes early,

00:03:21.020 --> 00:03:24.750
modern and Baroque studies,
Spanish Golden Age, fantasy

00:03:24.750 --> 00:03:28.970
and horror and cultural
criticism.

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:32.770
William Eggington is the Decker
Professor in the Humanities

00:03:32.770 --> 00:03:34.070
and the Director

00:03:34.070 --> 00:03:35.630
of the Alexander Grass
Humanities Institute

00:03:35.630 --> 00:03:37.570
at Johns Hopkins University

00:03:37.570 --> 00:03:39.840
where he also chairs
the Department of German

00:03:39.840 --> 00:03:42.610
and Romance Languages
and Literatures.

00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:45.710
He's the author, editor
or translator of more

00:03:45.710 --> 00:03:49.270
than a dozen books including,
"How the World Became a Stage",

00:03:49.270 --> 00:03:53.430
published in 2003 and "The
Man Who Invented Fiction,

00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:57.860
how Cervantes ushered in the
modern world", published in 2016

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:01.630
and that we had the pleasure
to present here in the library.

00:04:01.630 --> 00:04:05.290
His research and teaching
focuses in Spanish

00:04:05.290 --> 00:04:08.400
and Latin American literature,
literary theory and the relation

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:10.930
between literature
and philosophy.

00:04:10.930 --> 00:04:13.890
Patricia Vieira is an
Associate Professor of Spanish

00:04:13.890 --> 00:04:16.440
and Portuguese, Comparative
Literature, and Film

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:18.520
and Media Studies at
Georgetown University

00:04:18.520 --> 00:04:22.070
and she's also Associate
Research Professor at The Center

00:04:22.070 --> 00:04:25.420
for Social Studies of the
University of Coimbra.

00:04:25.420 --> 00:04:27.300
She's the editor of five
books and the author

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:30.650
of five books including
"Cinema no Estado Novo:

00:04:30.650 --> 00:04:34.840
a encenacao do regime",
published in 2011

00:04:34.840 --> 00:04:40.790
and the forthcoming book that's
going to come out in 2018 is

00:04:40.790 --> 00:04:44.540
"States of Grace: Utopia
in Brazilian Culture",

00:04:44.540 --> 00:04:46.720
which hopefully we'll have
her here at the library

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:48.240
to talk about it soon.

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:51.860
She also coedits the book
series "Future Perfect:

00:04:51.860 --> 00:04:54.970
Images of the Time to Come
in Philosophy, Politics

00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:57.910
and Cultural Studies"
and she cocurates a

00:04:57.910 --> 00:05:04.490
"Philosophical Salon" at
the L.A. Review of Books.

00:05:04.490 --> 00:05:06.330
I should let you know that
all of their books are here

00:05:06.330 --> 00:05:09.240
at the library, so
you're welcome to come

00:05:09.240 --> 00:05:12.550
and read them here with us.

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:14.520
So, please join me
in welcoming David,

00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:17.510
Will and Patricia
to the library.

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:26.590
[ Applause ]

