All right, what I'm going
to try and do here is spin

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:08.780
through a series of slides
that I have put together

00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:11.960
as a spin off from
the book for an event

00:06:11.960 --> 00:06:17.830
that the UB Alumni Relations
Office hosted last night here

00:06:17.830 --> 00:06:20.020
in town.

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:25.190
I had way more time to go
through the PowerPoint there,

00:06:25.190 --> 00:06:28.460
so excuse some of the crankiness
here because I'm going

00:06:28.460 --> 00:06:31.180
to really try to
cut this down into

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:35.110
about 15-20 minutes, we'll see.

00:06:35.110 --> 00:06:39.140
All right, how did we get here?

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:42.840
This is one of the most
interesting quotes you'll ever

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:44.380
read, I think.

00:06:44.380 --> 00:06:49.030
Ron Suskind, New York
Times Magazine contributor,

00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:51.630
in the summer of 2002, after
I had written an article

00:06:51.630 --> 00:06:53.210
in The Squire that
The White House didn't

00:06:53.210 --> 00:06:56.050
like about Bush's former
Communication Director,

00:06:56.050 --> 00:06:57.350
Karen Hughes.

00:06:57.350 --> 00:06:59.630
I had a meeting with a Senior
Adviser to Bush, he expressed:

00:06:59.630 --> 00:07:01.350
"The White House
is displeasured."

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:02.710
And then he told me something

00:07:02.710 --> 00:07:06.230
that at the time I didn't fully
comprehend, they said that guys

00:07:06.230 --> 00:07:09.980
like me were in what we call
the reality-based community

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:12.920
which he defined as people who
believe that solutions emerge

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:16.420
from your judicious study
of the discernable reality.

00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:19.870
I nodded. -- That's not the way
the world really works anymore

00:07:19.870 --> 00:07:22.600
-- he continued -- we're an
empire now and when we act,

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:26.430
we create our reality and while
you're studying that reality,

00:07:26.430 --> 00:07:28.270
judiciously as you
will, we'll act again,

00:07:28.270 --> 00:07:31.060
creating other new realities
which you can study, too.

00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:32.630
And that's how things
will sort out.

00:07:32.630 --> 00:07:35.430
We're history factors and
you, all of you, will be left

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:40.730
to just study what we do --
So, this is from Dr. Who, 1977,

00:07:40.730 --> 00:07:42.900
"You know, the very powerful and
the very stupid have one thing

00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:45.100
in common: they don't alter
their views to fit the facts,

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:47.380
but they alter the
facts to fit their views

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:49.770
which can be uncomfortable
if you happen to be one

00:07:49.770 --> 00:07:51.870
of the facts that
needs altering."

00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:54.360
[Audience laughter].

00:07:54.360 --> 00:07:58.090
There is a brand-new
technology that allows

00:07:58.090 --> 00:08:01.510
for diminished reality.

00:08:01.510 --> 00:08:05.040
[ Video playing ]

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:06.840
I'm just going to play
a little bit of this.

00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:56.160
[ Music ]

00:08:56.160 --> 00:08:58.910
&gt;&gt; David R Castillo: All right,
well you get the point there.

00:08:58.910 --> 00:09:00.930
Things just disappear
in front of your eyes

00:09:00.930 --> 00:09:02.400
and the technology is so fast

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:06.270
that really actually
once you program this,

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:11.790
the actual filtering, it
can happen in real time,

00:09:11.790 --> 00:09:15.510
so let's see if I can
get back to, all right.

00:09:15.510 --> 00:09:20.110
[ Music ]

00:09:20.110 --> 00:09:23.920
Oh, it's going backwards now.

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:25.220
There we go.

00:09:25.220 --> 00:09:26.630
So, one possible application

00:09:26.630 --> 00:09:29.510
of this diminishing reality
technology: "Take Google Glass,

00:09:29.510 --> 00:09:31.320
the company's overhyped
'smart glasses'

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:34.100
which can automatically snap
photos of everything we see

00:09:34.100 --> 00:09:37.440
and store them for posterity.

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:40.520
But smart glasses
could do so much more!

00:09:40.520 --> 00:09:42.330
Why not edit out
disturbing sights

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:44.320
that haunt us on
the way to work?

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:48.240
Just last year the futurist
Ayesha Khanna even described

00:09:48.240 --> 00:09:51.340
smart contact lenses that could
make homeless people disappear

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:55.300
from view, 'enhancing our
basic sense' and, undoubtedly,

00:09:55.300 --> 00:09:57.070
making our lives so
much more enjoyable.

00:09:57.070 --> 00:09:59.560
In a way, this does solve the
problem of homelessness --

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:02.670
unless, of course, you happen
to be a homeless person.

00:10:02.670 --> 00:10:04.700
In that case, Silicon
Valley would hand you a pair

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:07.780
of overpriced glasses that would
make the streets feel like home.

00:10:07.780 --> 00:10:11.710
To quote an ad for Samsung's
fancy TV sets, 'Reality.

00:10:11.710 --> 00:10:15.180
What a letdown.'"

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:18.640
All right and here we go, this
would be augmented reality.

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:20.790
[Video starts].

00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:23.700
&gt;&gt; Everything started
with this selfie.

00:10:23.700 --> 00:10:27.320
It shows 18-year-old Syrian
refugee Anas Modamani [phonetic]

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:29.530
with the most powerful
woman in the world.

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:31.120
The photograph was taken

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:34.330
when German Chancellor Angela
Merkel visited a refugee shelter

00:10:34.330 --> 00:10:35.630
in Berlin.

00:10:35.630 --> 00:10:37.580
Modamani had just
arrived in Germany

00:10:37.580 --> 00:10:39.520
and was full of confidence.

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:41.930
Today, almost one and
a half years later,

00:10:41.930 --> 00:10:43.480
he has disillusioned.

00:10:43.480 --> 00:10:45.760
His picture went
viral around the world

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:48.060
and it is haunting him.

00:10:51.510 --> 00:10:54.040
[ Speaking Arabic ]

00:10:54.040 --> 00:10:56.170
Since 2015, it has
been used three

00:10:56.170 --> 00:10:58.510
or four times for fake news.

00:10:58.510 --> 00:11:02.230
[ Speaking Arabic ]

00:11:02.230 --> 00:11:04.050
The first time my
picture was linked

00:11:04.050 --> 00:11:06.510
to the terror attack
in Brussels.

00:11:06.510 --> 00:11:10.040
[ Speaking Arabic ]

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:13.500
The last time they said
I was involved in a crime

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:16.730
where six attackers set fire
to a sleeping homeless man

00:11:16.730 --> 00:11:19.510
in a Berlin subway station.

00:11:19.510 --> 00:11:24.810
[ Speaking Arabic ]

00:11:24.810 --> 00:11:27.920
All these allegations
are absolutely untrue,

00:11:27.920 --> 00:11:29.840
but they were published
on Facebook

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:32.900
and shared more than
1,000 times.

00:11:32.900 --> 00:11:34.950
Again, and again, Anas Modamani

00:11:34.950 --> 00:11:36.520
and his lawyer reported
the images

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:38.710
and asked Facebook
to remove them.

00:11:38.710 --> 00:11:42.710
The company says it did.

00:11:42.710 --> 00:11:45.420
"We are sorry to hear about
Mr. Modamani's concerns

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:47.750
with the way some people
have used his image.

00:11:47.750 --> 00:11:50.300
We have already quickly
disabled access to content

00:11:50.300 --> 00:11:52.170
that has been accurately
reported to us

00:11:52.170 --> 00:11:54.620
by Mr. Modamani's
legal representatives,

00:11:54.620 --> 00:11:57.640
so we do not believe that
legal action here is necessary

00:11:57.640 --> 00:12:02.160
or that it is the most effective
way to resolve the situation."

00:12:02.160 --> 00:12:06.050
But for Anas Modamani,
that's not good enough.

00:12:06.050 --> 00:12:08.320
His lawyer says the images
are still in circulation

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:12.790
on the platform and he's taking
Facebook to court over it.

00:12:12.790 --> 00:12:15.560
We want Facebook to delete the
picture from the whole network

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:18.930
and for them to make sure it
cannot be uploaded anymore.

00:12:18.930 --> 00:12:22.150
Anas Modamani cannot find out
himself where his picture is,

00:12:22.150 --> 00:12:24.590
it has been shared
more than 1,000 times.

00:12:24.590 --> 00:12:26.950
The only one who is able
to do so is Facebook

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:29.750
and Facebook is also
responsible for making sure

00:12:29.750 --> 00:12:31.920
that the picture is not
circulating any longer.

00:12:31.920 --> 00:12:34.750
The trial starts today

00:12:34.750 --> 00:12:37.210
at The Regional Court
in Southern Germany.

00:12:37.210 --> 00:12:39.580
The case could have
enormous repercussions

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:42.710
if the judges decide that
Facebook can be held accountable

00:12:42.710 --> 00:12:45.060
for the distribution
of fake news.

00:12:45.060 --> 00:12:48.550
&gt;&gt; David R Castillo: Well,
so the trial took place

00:12:48.550 --> 00:12:54.280
and Facebook was not
held accountable.

00:12:54.280 --> 00:13:00.480
So, I guess it's this one
that's working -- Yes, got it.

00:13:00.480 --> 00:13:05.420
So, yes. Nothing happened there.

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:07.720
Let's see --

00:13:12.790 --> 00:13:16.240
This is another case, it's
a little bit long-ish,

00:13:16.240 --> 00:13:22.370
so I'm going to -- Maybe
we can play it later

00:13:22.370 --> 00:13:25.280
if there is a question about
fake news, if people want

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:27.420
to talk about this
a little bit more.

00:13:27.420 --> 00:13:30.950
This is a case in
Idaho actually,

00:13:30.950 --> 00:13:36.150
it was reported about
a week ago.

00:13:36.150 --> 00:13:43.160
So, Facebook agrees to
release ration pars ads,

00:13:43.160 --> 00:13:46.380
pledges deeper look at
2016 elections, Zuckerberg,

00:13:46.380 --> 00:13:48.650
as you may remember,
projected the criticism

00:13:48.650 --> 00:13:50.560
at first saying shortly
after the election

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:53.860
that it's a pretty crazy
idea to think that fake news

00:13:53.860 --> 00:13:56.390
on Facebook influenced
the election in any way.

00:13:56.390 --> 00:13:58.510
He added that voters make
their decisions based

00:13:58.510 --> 00:14:00.960
on lived experience,
but Facebook had

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:03.760
to change its tone early
this month when it disclosed

00:14:03.760 --> 00:14:05.080
that a ration company known

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:07.610
as The Internet Research
Agency had bought more

00:14:07.610 --> 00:14:10.790
than 3,000 politically charged
ads worth about, I don't know,

00:14:10.790 --> 00:14:14.500
about $150,000 on its
platform during key periods

00:14:14.500 --> 00:14:16.620
of the presidential campaign,
often dealing with issues

00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:18.780
such as race, immigration
and gun rights.

00:14:18.780 --> 00:14:23.450
We got a Twitter response:
"The ration hoax continues,

00:14:23.450 --> 00:14:25.950
now it's ads on Facebook,
what about the totally biased

00:14:25.950 --> 00:14:29.590
and dishonest media coverage
in favor of crooked Hillary?

00:14:29.590 --> 00:14:32.180
The greatest influence over our
election was the fake news media

00:14:32.180 --> 00:14:35.060
screaming for Hillary Clinton."

00:14:36.270 --> 00:14:40.610
Of course, you may remember
these instants here.

00:14:40.610 --> 00:14:46.230
Let's see, this may not
play, but very quickly,

00:14:46.230 --> 00:14:48.750
this is the famous interview

00:14:48.750 --> 00:14:55.610
where Kellyanne Conway
coined the famous expression

00:14:55.610 --> 00:14:58.710
"alternative fact".

00:14:58.710 --> 00:15:04.360
So, shortly after I picked up
this article from the internet:

00:15:04.360 --> 00:15:06.970
"The public relation society
of America put out a statement

00:15:06.970 --> 00:15:08.870
on alternative facts
condemning the phrase

