01:00:31.970 --> 01:00:37.800
as effective -- And we could
even imagine the possibility

01:00:37.800 --> 01:00:39.910
that we would want to
become vampires [laughter]

01:00:39.910 --> 01:00:43.140
in a form, but zombies?

01:00:43.140 --> 01:00:45.860
Who would want to
become a zombie?

01:00:45.860 --> 01:00:49.480
So, really that kind of
brought me to thinking

01:00:49.480 --> 01:00:57.160
about why the popularity of
zombies, what kind of anxieties,

01:00:57.160 --> 01:01:00.220
you know, individual

01:01:00.220 --> 01:01:05.080
and collective anxieties
were being exercised or dealt

01:01:05.080 --> 01:01:12.760
with through the representation
of zombies and I think

01:01:12.760 --> 01:01:14.150
at this point, you know,

01:01:14.150 --> 01:01:21.690
I mentioned that 1984 was the
number one selling book in 2017.

01:01:21.690 --> 01:01:27.900
The success of The Handmaid's
Tale is another example.

01:01:27.900 --> 01:01:35.060
&gt;&gt; Going back to the [inaudible]
Tale is not really drawing

01:01:35.060 --> 01:01:38.340
from what [inaudible] I'm
just curious about that.

01:01:38.340 --> 01:01:40.070
&gt;&gt; David R Castillo:
Right, so there is a new way

01:01:40.070 --> 01:01:45.000
of Dystopias right now and
they are coming out like crazy

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:46.810
within five or ten years
we're going to have

01:01:46.810 --> 01:01:49.080
to examine the whole
canon of Dystopias.

01:01:49.080 --> 01:01:53.850
They are coming out with
incredible speed and we have to,

01:01:53.850 --> 01:01:57.720
once again, try to, you
know, figure out what is it

01:01:57.720 --> 01:02:04.120
that makes Dystopias such
powerful tools to relate,

01:02:04.120 --> 01:02:08.650
to comment to our world and
the same thing could be said

01:02:08.650 --> 01:02:12.370
about humor so I
showed there a couple

01:02:12.370 --> 01:02:18.830
of books by Steven Goldberg.

01:02:18.830 --> 01:02:26.360
There is more of a-- In some
ways, we're going back to a time

01:02:26.360 --> 01:02:34.280
where traditional genre
divisions don't hold that well,

01:02:34.280 --> 01:02:36.020
so we thought, you know,

01:02:36.020 --> 01:02:40.080
the talk show commentators
are now book authors

01:02:40.080 --> 01:02:43.480
and the other way around, we
have shows that turn into books

01:02:43.480 --> 01:02:47.210
and books that turn into
shows, but the theme

01:02:47.210 --> 01:02:52.100
of irony is another very
powerful weapon right now

01:02:52.100 --> 01:02:57.970
in our world and this speaks
to a certain need that we have,

01:02:57.970 --> 01:03:01.280
we believe, to examine filters

01:03:01.280 --> 01:03:03.210
and irony is a very
powerful weapon to do

01:03:03.210 --> 01:03:06.790
that because it implies
a certain obliqueness

01:03:06.790 --> 01:03:09.030
that allows us to
see a double image,

01:03:09.030 --> 01:03:11.290
sort of in an anamorphic way.

01:03:11.290 --> 01:03:13.730
&gt;&gt; William Egginton: We think
one of the potential powers

01:03:13.730 --> 01:03:17.310
of literature and reading
books, not just analytic books

01:03:17.310 --> 01:03:18.610
and nonfiction books

01:03:18.610 --> 01:03:21.580
but actually fictional books
is the power of literature

01:03:21.580 --> 01:03:23.910
and the written word
in particular,

01:03:23.910 --> 01:03:26.500
but we do analyze television
shows and we talk about movies,

01:03:26.500 --> 01:03:29.380
but that literature and the
written word has a focusing the

01:03:29.380 --> 01:03:32.680
attention on invisible filters.

01:03:32.680 --> 01:03:34.830
You don't see these filter
per se but they're there,

01:03:34.830 --> 01:03:38.090
the filters that we spend the
entire book talking about.

01:03:38.090 --> 01:03:43.230
Literature can animate the
senses to pay attention

01:03:43.230 --> 01:03:49.690
to how our reality is posed for
someone who is living in it,

01:03:49.690 --> 01:03:54.130
how a particular media
environment situates something

01:03:54.130 --> 01:03:57.210
for someone who's
imbued or immersed

01:03:57.210 --> 01:03:58.510
in that media environment.

01:03:58.510 --> 01:04:00.940
We talk a lot about
Cervantes which is, of course,

01:04:00.940 --> 01:04:04.910
old literature, but we also
make the argument and it's one

01:04:04.910 --> 01:04:07.920
that I went into
great length to work

01:04:07.920 --> 01:04:10.860
out in my intellectual
biography of Cervantes the man

01:04:10.860 --> 01:04:14.670
who invented fiction, that why
I make this outlander standing

01:04:14.670 --> 01:04:16.170
claim that he invented
fiction is

01:04:16.170 --> 01:04:17.890
because we have certain
expectations

01:04:17.890 --> 01:04:21.280
in modern fiction all of
which can be traced past back

01:04:21.280 --> 01:04:24.000
to what he was able to do with
the text it was precisely that.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:25.900
Our expectations of characters

01:04:25.900 --> 01:04:27.270
as being three-dimensional
people

01:04:27.270 --> 01:04:30.850
that we can somehow relate
to, that integrate themselves

01:04:30.850 --> 01:04:32.690
with our sense of
empathy with something

01:04:32.690 --> 01:04:34.630
that he created and
how did he do it?

01:04:34.630 --> 01:04:37.190
By making other characters
who are both bewildered by

01:04:37.190 --> 01:04:39.980
and capable of analyzing
and thinking critically

01:04:39.980 --> 01:04:43.100
about their relationship
to media

01:04:43.100 --> 01:04:48.100
and to the truth laying outside
that media, so I think often

01:04:48.100 --> 01:04:50.500
about a wonderful interview,
and you should look it up,

01:04:50.500 --> 01:04:53.320
I can't remember what
publication published it

01:04:53.320 --> 01:04:57.400
but it was an interview between
the novelist Marilynne Robinson

01:04:57.400 --> 01:05:01.960
and our former President
in which he expressed,

01:05:01.960 --> 01:05:03.370
because he's a great
reader of novels

01:05:03.370 --> 01:05:06.530
and he expressed this worry
in an age that is reading less

01:05:06.530 --> 01:05:10.000
and less literature in the
sense of the presentation

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:12.340
of realistic characters
that we can have empathetic

01:05:12.340 --> 01:05:13.640
relationships with.

01:05:13.640 --> 01:05:16.800
What is it doing to our
capacity to empathize?

01:05:16.800 --> 01:05:20.620
And the neuroscientific
research on precisely

01:05:20.620 --> 01:05:23.040
that topic does give
some credence

01:05:23.040 --> 01:05:27.460
to the President's
sense of alarm, right?

01:05:27.460 --> 01:05:29.940
Because apparently
reading novels,

01:05:29.940 --> 01:05:32.470
more than any other consumption
of fictional narratives

01:05:32.470 --> 01:05:38.570
in other words, media in
what we call a hotter way

01:05:38.570 --> 01:05:40.930
where you have less of
an ability to filter

01:05:40.930 --> 01:05:43.700
and use your own
imagination to create.

01:05:43.700 --> 01:05:48.030
Reading novels in particular
ignites our ability to empathize

01:05:48.030 --> 01:05:49.810
with those who are
different from us, all right?

01:05:49.810 --> 01:05:52.330
And this is something
that we see in the history

01:05:52.330 --> 01:05:58.110
of the modern novel from as far
back as Cervantes up to novelist

01:05:58.110 --> 01:06:03.950
like Valeria Luiselli or Karl
Ove Knausgaard or so many others

01:06:03.950 --> 01:06:06.560
that I could think of.

01:06:06.560 --> 01:06:07.860
&gt;&gt; Patricia Vieira:
Any other questions?

01:06:07.860 --> 01:06:12.320
I do have a question and
you refer in the book

01:06:12.320 --> 01:06:15.980
that today's mediology
turns copies into things,

01:06:15.980 --> 01:06:19.140
so things that proliferated
as copies become reality

01:06:19.140 --> 01:06:23.530
and this tends to sideline
reality itself, right?

01:06:23.530 --> 01:06:27.970
And you link this to the
current ecological crisis

01:06:27.970 --> 01:06:31.080
because reality as such
becomes expandable and so,

01:06:31.080 --> 01:06:33.380
you can just expose of it.

01:06:33.380 --> 01:06:36.900
And I was wondering if
you see also literature

01:06:36.900 --> 01:06:40.230
or the creative arts,
let's call them like this,

01:06:40.230 --> 01:06:44.060
as a way to counter
this phenomenon.

01:06:44.060 --> 01:06:45.860
&gt;&gt; William Egginton: I think
very much we do and we think

01:06:45.860 --> 01:06:48.540
of literature and creativity and
the arts as one of the only ways

01:06:48.540 --> 01:06:49.840
of countering this phenomenon.

01:06:49.840 --> 01:06:52.210
So, what you're referring to
is in the second age of media

01:06:52.210 --> 01:06:57.290
that turns copies into
things, our idea of the world

01:06:57.290 --> 01:07:04.390
as a totality of the world
being a representation

01:07:04.390 --> 01:07:06.800
that gets packaged
into something

01:07:06.800 --> 01:07:10.240
that is itself bottomless,
so the world

01:07:10.240 --> 01:07:13.240
as that what supports us becomes
something like a commodity

01:07:13.240 --> 01:07:15.970
which means it has and end, it
can be thought of as a resource

01:07:15.970 --> 01:07:18.780
that we can expend, and of
course, we need to think

01:07:18.780 --> 01:07:21.990
about it in those terms, but
at the same time once we think

01:07:21.990 --> 01:07:24.960
of the very source of
life itself, of everything

01:07:24.960 --> 01:07:28.150
that we are, not as something
infinite and grounding

01:07:28.150 --> 01:07:31.700
but as one granted
very, very big,

01:07:31.700 --> 01:07:36.080
but one resource
among many this kind

01:07:36.080 --> 01:07:38.590
of opens the door
into a scary future.

01:07:38.590 --> 01:07:42.290
You begin to think of
everything in terms

01:07:42.290 --> 01:07:45.350
of potential commodities,
people are commodities,

01:07:45.350 --> 01:07:48.340
life sources are commodities
as opposed of thinking

01:07:48.340 --> 01:07:54.150
about what is the potential
value of these sources

01:07:54.150 --> 01:07:57.380
of these things in their
own terms, not in terms

01:07:57.380 --> 01:08:00.520
of what they might be
calculable in dollars.

01:08:00.520 --> 01:08:04.510
We do find that art and
literature are precisely anchors

01:08:04.510 --> 01:08:06.170
that keep us from
falling entirely

01:08:06.170 --> 01:08:08.000
over the cliff in that sense.

01:08:08.000 --> 01:08:09.300
&gt;&gt; David R Castillo: Yes,

01:08:09.300 --> 01:08:17.700
and we also mentioned
the tourist industry,

01:08:17.700 --> 01:08:22.720
sort of the ultimate
paradigm of that kind

01:08:22.720 --> 01:08:28.780
of dialectic negation
that takes place.

01:08:28.780 --> 01:08:34.520
In the book we also
mentioned a recent example

01:08:34.520 --> 01:08:40.800
of the American Airlines
mural that is displayed

01:08:40.800 --> 01:08:48.110
over the JFK security area, you
know, it's called the skyline

01:08:48.110 --> 01:09:00.420
of the world and it
shows a rather unreal,

01:09:00.420 --> 01:09:04.670
Disney World-like
picture of globalization

01:09:04.670 --> 01:09:09.670
where you have Eiffel Tower,
with the Empire State Building

01:09:09.670 --> 01:09:13.250
with other landmarks
throughout the world,

01:09:13.250 --> 01:09:17.200
the skyline of the world.

01:09:17.200 --> 01:09:21.670
As you walk through security,
the reality of you having

01:09:21.670 --> 01:09:24.190
to take your shoes of,
take your belt off,

01:09:24.190 --> 01:09:29.160
you know, do a spread eagle.

01:09:29.160 --> 01:09:34.780
It's funny, don't know how
much you actually to share

01:09:34.780 --> 01:09:42.380
of this reality, but a Spaniard
that shaves only inconsistently,

01:09:42.380 --> 01:09:43.940
coming through security,

01:09:43.940 --> 01:09:48.410
the notion that one the one
hand you have unlimited movement

01:09:48.410 --> 01:09:50.640
of the mural, where
you are a citizen,

01:09:50.640 --> 01:09:53.950
you are being interpellated as
a citizen, a global citizen,

01:09:53.950 --> 01:09:57.260
a citizen, skyline of the world

01:09:57.260 --> 01:10:00.080
and at the same time you're
taking your belt off and going

01:10:00.080 --> 01:10:04.480
through increasingly
oppressive measures

01:10:04.480 --> 01:10:09.000
that show you the exact
opposite, you know,

01:10:09.000 --> 01:10:13.600
that opens up the room
for question to think

01:10:13.600 --> 01:10:20.420
about if this image is true
and what is it negating?

01:10:20.420 --> 01:10:24.320
Like the tourist industry,
like Disney World, you know,

01:10:24.320 --> 01:10:28.700
it negates oppression,
colonialism.

01:10:28.700 --> 01:10:31.170
&gt;&gt; William Egginton: The
90% of the population

01:10:31.170 --> 01:10:33.340
who doesn't have
the capacity to walk

01:10:33.340 --> 01:10:35.580
through security
to another country.

01:10:35.580 --> 01:10:36.880
&gt;&gt; David R Castillo: Exactly,

01:10:36.880 --> 01:10:41.390
yes and that's part
of the thinking.

01:10:41.390 --> 01:10:47.330
Once we look at the
world in these terms,

01:10:47.330 --> 01:10:54.540
once we train ourselves in
the art of reality literacy,

01:10:54.540 --> 01:11:02.320
in a way you can apply
that skill to literature,

01:11:02.320 --> 01:11:09.150
to the American Airlines
Mural, to the tourist industry

01:11:09.150 --> 01:11:13.070
in search for that
allusive manifestation

01:11:13.070 --> 01:11:19.150
of the truth in the
filter itself.

